<h2 id=3D"idx_how_to_calculate_the_area_of_a_segment">How to Calculate the =
Area of a Segment</h2>
<p>
A segment is a part of a circle separated by a <em>chord</em> connecting tw=
o points on the circle=E2=80=99s edge. Think of a segment as a part of a ci=
rcle that has been sliced off using a straight line.
</p>
<p>
A segment is often represented as part of a sector, as seen in the image be=
low. The segment is the shaded part of the sector.
</p>
<div class=3D"article-thumbnail article-thumbnail-width-50">
<img loading=3D"lazy" decoding=3D"async" src=3D"https://www.inchcalculator.=
com/a/img/shapes/circular-segment.png" alt=3D"diagram of a circular segment=
 showing the radius, central angle, chord length, height, and arc length" w=
idth=3D"1280" height=3D"854">
</div>
<p>
In addition to area, a segment is defined by its height (also called the sa=
gitta), chord length, and arc length. The <a href=3D"https://www.inchcalcul=
ator.com/area-calculator/">area</a> of a segment can be found using a simpl=
e formula.
</p><div id=3D"AdThrive_Content_1_tablet" class=3D"adthrive-ad  adthrive-co=
ntent adthrive-content-1" style=3D"min-height: 250px;"></div>
<h3 id=3D"idx_segment_area_formula">Segment Area Formula</h3>
<p>
The area can be found using the segment area formula:
</p>
<p>
<span class=3D"formula formula--bg-grey">segment area =3D <span class=3D"fr=
action" aria-label=3D"fraction with r to the 2 power times ( theta  minus s=
in( theta )) over 2"><span class=3D"num">r=C2=B2 =C3=97 (=CE=B8 =E2=80=93 s=
in(=CE=B8))</span><span class=3D"visually-hidden"> / </span><span class=3D"=
den">2</span></span></span>
</p>
<p>
Thus, a segment=E2=80=99s area is equal to the <a href=3D"https://www.inchc=
alculator.com/radius-calculator/">radius</a> <em>r</em> squared, times the =
central angle <em>=CE=B8</em> in radians minus the sine of =CE=B8, divided =
by 2.
</p>
<p>
Note that the central angle must be in radians for this equation to work. I=
f you have the central angle in degrees, use our <a href=3D"https://www.inc=
hcalculator.com/convert/degree-to-radian/">degrees to radians converter</a>=
 to convert to radians, or use the equation in the next section.
</p><div id=3D"AdThrive_Content_2_tablet" class=3D"adthrive-ad  adthrive-co=
ntent adthrive-content-2" style=3D"min-height: 250px;"></div>
<div class=3D"article-thumbnail article-thumbnail-width-80">
<img loading=3D"lazy" decoding=3D"async" src=3D"https://www.inchcalculator.=
com/wp-content/uploads/2023/03/segment-area-formula.png" alt=3D"Graphic sho=
wing the segment area formula where the area is equal to the radius squared=
, times the central angle minus the sine of central angle, divided by 2." w=
idth=3D"1280" height=3D"854" class=3D"alignnone size-full wp-image-11624">
</div>
<div class=3D"panel panel--bg-grey">
<p>
<strong>For example,</strong> let=E2=80=99s find the area of a segment for =
a circle with a radius of 17 and a central angle of 1.25 radians.
</p>
<p class=3D"formula formula--bg-primary">
<span>segment area =3D <span class=3D"fraction" aria-label=3D"fraction with=
 17 to the 2 power times (1.25 minus sin(1.25)) over 2"><span class=3D"num"=
>17=C2=B2 =C3=97 (1.25 =E2=80=93 sin(1.25))</span><span class=3D"visually-h=
idden"> / </span><span class=3D"den">2</span></span></span><br>
<span>segment area =3D <span class=3D"fraction" aria-label=3D"fraction with=
 289 times (1.25 minus 0.094898) over 2"><span class=3D"num">289 =C3=97 (1.=
25 =E2=80=93 0.094898)</span><span class=3D"visually-hidden"> / </span><spa=
n class=3D"den">2</span></span></span><br>
<span>segment area =3D <span class=3D"fraction" aria-label=3D"fraction with=
 289 times 0.301021) over 2"><span class=3D"num">289 =C3=97 0.301021)</span=
><span class=3D"visually-hidden"> / </span><span class=3D"den">2</span></sp=
an></span><br>
<span>segment area =3D <span class=3D"fraction" aria-label=3D"fraction with=
 86.995 over 2"><span class=3D"num">86.995</span><span class=3D"visually-hi=
dden"> / </span><span class=3D"den">2</span></span></span><br>
<span>segment area =3D 43.497</span>
</p>
<p>
Thus, the segment area is <strong>43.497</strong>.
</p>
</div>
<h3 id=3D"idx_segment_area_formula_for_a_central_angle_in_degrees">Segment =
Area Formula for a Central Angle in Degrees</h3>
<p>
If you want to find the area of a segment, but your central angle is in deg=
rees instead of radians, you can find the area using the following formula:
</p><div id=3D"AdThrive_Content_3_tablet" class=3D"adthrive-ad  adthrive-co=
ntent adthrive-content-3" style=3D"min-height: 250px;"></div>
<p>
<span class=3D"formula formula--bg-grey">segment area =3D r=C2=B2 =C3=97 ((=
=CE=B8 =C3=97 =CF=80)/180 =E2=80=93 sin(=CE=B8))/2</span>
</p>
<p>
This is essentially the same formula as above, but the <span class=3D"formu=
la formula-small">(=CE=B8 =C3=97 =CF=80)/180</span> part converts the angle=
 to radians.
</p>
<h2 id=3D"idx_how_to_find_the_height_of_a_segment">How to Find the Height o=
f a Segment</h2>
<p>
The following formula defines the height, or sagitta, of a segment.
</p><div id=3D"AdThrive_Content_4_tablet" class=3D"adthrive-ad  adthrive-co=
ntent adthrive-content-4" style=3D"min-height: 250px;"></div>
<p>
<span class=3D"formula formula--bg-grey">segment height =3D r =C3=97 (1 =E2=
=80=93 cos(<span class=3D"fraction" aria-label=3D"fraction with  theta  ove=
r 2"><span class=3D"num">=CE=B8</span><span class=3D"visually-hidden"> / </=
span><span class=3D"den">2</span></span>))</span>
</p>
<p>
The height of a segment is equal to the radius <em>r</em> times 1 minus the=
 cosine of the central angle <em>=CE=B8</em> in radians divided by 2. Note =
here that again, the central angle must be in radians, not degrees.
</p>
<h2 id=3D"idx_how_to_find_the_arc_length_of_a_segment">How to Find the Arc =
Length of a Segment</h2>
<p>
The arc of a segment is the rounded outer portion of the circle that connec=
ts the two radii of the circle. The <a href=3D"https://www.inchcalculator.c=
om/arc-length-calculator/">arc length</a> can be found using the formula:
</p><div id=3D"AdThrive_Content_5_tablet" class=3D"adthrive-ad  adthrive-co=
ntent adthrive-content-5" style=3D"min-height: 250px;"></div>
<p>
<span class=3D"formula formula--bg-grey">arc length (s) =3D radius (r) =C3=
=97 central angle (=CE=B8)</span>
</p>
<p>
The arc length <em>s</em> of a segment is equal to the radius <em>r</em> ti=
mes the central angle <em>=CE=B8</em> in radians. Again, as with most of th=
e above equations, the central angle must be in radians, not degrees.
</p>
<p>
You might also be interested in our <a href=3D"https://www.inchcalculator.c=
om/sector-area-calculator/">sector area calculator</a> for solving the part=
s of a sector.</p>
                    </div>

